So we're going to talk about that.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:40.760
Now, before we get into that whole side of things, let's just start with your story.

00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:41.960
How did you get into programming in Python?

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:45.260
I actually got into programming not through university or anything like that.

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:47.960
I actually studied to become a doctor.

00:02:47.960 --> 00:02:52.220
And partly because when I was growing up, my parents were really keen on me becoming a doctor.

00:02:52.220 --> 00:02:53.460
So, yeah, I'll be a good kid.

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:54.700
I'll try and become a doctor.

00:02:54.700 --> 00:02:56.340
Then I kind of discovered photography.

00:02:56.340 --> 00:02:58.800
And I got really, really into that in high school.

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:05.200
And I got so excited about that that my plans for kind of going to, say, kind of Oxbridge or something basically fell by the wayside.

00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:08.580
And I got really, really into studying things like media and film.

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:17.320
And I went from there to basically study, yeah, photography, filmmaking, video production, stuff like that, playing with these things.

00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:19.260
And I'm showing my age when I say this now.

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:21.400
But I was this is around the turn of the century.

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:25.520
We were just starting to kind of start playing with things like Final Cut Pro and digital video.

00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:29.220
Because when I was studying this, we were literally, you know, like cut and paste.

00:03:29.220 --> 00:03:29.760
Yes.

00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:31.040
I ran it with cut.

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:36.780
We were, when we were making films, we were using like hand winding films, a kind of Bolex camera.

00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:40.660
We literally had to kind of cut film and paste it to make films.

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:44.600
That is a really, really hard way to edit video together, right?

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:48.140
I mean, now it's like splice, splice, splice, digital this, transforms that.

00:03:48.140 --> 00:03:48.840
It's crazy.

00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:50.020
But that's how it was, right?

00:03:50.060 --> 00:03:54.320
Like the world has changed so much in 20, 30 years and it's easy to forget.

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:54.660
Exactly.

00:03:54.660 --> 00:03:55.460
So we did this.

00:03:55.460 --> 00:04:03.500
And at the time there was this thing which was called New Media, which was other ways of kind of expressing yourself or exploring things.

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:06.280
And through that, there was this kind of interest in this thing called digital.

00:04:06.280 --> 00:04:13.120
So I kind of started playing around with things like Dreamweaver or ActionScript or stuff like this.

00:04:13.120 --> 00:04:14.780
And I thought, wow, this is kind of cool.

00:04:14.780 --> 00:04:23.020
Like because there was a load of really interesting art in this field right now because people were trying to explore the medium and what any of that's actually meant.

00:04:23.020 --> 00:04:27.060
What kind of kind of impact it would have socially for us, really.

00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:33.100
And on the course I was studying, you are basically given quite a lot of freedom, almost too much freedom.

00:04:33.100 --> 00:04:40.420
So when we end up graduating, a lot of us had kind of black and white films about ourselves, which was I didn't find that interesting myself.

00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:54.980
But we also had a chance to just like mess around with computers to either explore an idea or I guess like try and build some kind of installation or something, which would help you interrogate an idea that you might have come across in the kind of art culture part.

00:04:54.980 --> 00:04:59.100
And we had a kind of media education part of the course I did.

00:04:59.100 --> 00:05:04.140
And a large part was about things like, say, media ownership and things like the California ideology.

00:05:04.140 --> 00:05:12.420
And there were loads of really wild ideas that came across, which in the turn of the century seemed like bonkers concepts.

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:17.380
There was this idea called surveillance, like the way we might kind of relate to computers.

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:24.720
Like you had kind of cultural commentators and artists talking about imagine what it's going to be like when everyone has computers and everyone can film everything.

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:25.020
Right.

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:25.580
Yeah.

00:05:25.580 --> 00:05:28.080
And now here we are with our cell phones, right?

00:05:28.080 --> 00:05:28.940
Like it's here.

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:29.280
Yeah.

00:05:29.280 --> 00:05:29.860
Like the thing.

00:05:29.860 --> 00:05:31.520
So I got into this idea.

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:38.180
And one of the things I started working, I really got interested in was this idea by this theorist called Jamekassio.

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:39.780
I think I pronounced his name properly.

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:42.780
He spoke about this idea of the participatory panopticon.

00:05:42.780 --> 00:05:50.200
Like when we all have cameras, there will be no real concept of privacy and will forever be kind of recording things and sharing things.

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:55.020
And there was this kind of idea that rather than having kind of big brother, there was millions of little brothers.

00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:59.940
And that has all kinds of ramifications on how like how we relate to each other.

00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:04.060
So I built I ended up working with a friend of mine because I couldn't really code at this point.

00:06:04.060 --> 00:06:07.200
I was just like some I don't know, some art student, really.

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:11.520
And I lived in a part of town which was kind of rough because I didn't know how hard it would be.

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:29.220
I thought, well, maybe we can like get a Linux box, find a way to run it in the car, run it off a like 15 pound webcam, connect to some GPS and some Wi-Fi, run this all off the cigarette lighter of the car and build something like a kind of panopticon thing for ourselves to see how that might change how we think about it.

00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:42.400
Yeah. And because we had this whole notion of because on the course, there was all this conversation about, say, the kind of Californian ideology and Silicon Valley in this way that in many cases, lots of companies present themselves as changing the world.

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:46.600
We figured, well, maybe we can kind of dress up in some of that language to explore this as an idea.

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:54.180
So rather than make a film, I figured, let's try to create some kind of intervention using open source software and a kind of cultural, I guess, thing.

00:06:54.180 --> 00:07:03.840
So I basically built this thing with a friend of mine or more specifically, my friend did all the coding whilst I was learning how to kind of code and kind of do some of this and work out what a ring buffer was and everything.

00:07:03.840 --> 00:07:11.920
And we built a thing which basically was a giant red button on a dashboard hooked up to a webcam that ran a ring buff in front of you.

00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:23.040
And what would happen is when you're driving around, if someone cuts you up, rather than screaming at them, because who knows, they might be carrying a knife or a gun or something, you'd pull over and you just hit this button like,

00:07:23.580 --> 00:07:35.920
Oh, God damn it. Why can't they drive properly? And that would catch where and how that person almost hit you with the idea being that when you drive home, when you're on the Wi-Fi, you'd upload this video to like YouTube or somewhere.

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:41.460
And the great thing about this is that, well, cars have really handy foreign keys called number plates.

00:07:41.460 --> 00:07:46.580
And if you can then expose a feed of this, you could create some kind of business model around this.

00:07:46.580 --> 00:07:52.400
So we kind of, as a kind of, I don't know, artsy statement, accidentally ended up building dashcams.

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:52.940
All right.

00:07:52.940 --> 00:07:54.480
Right. Yeah, exactly.

00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:58.220
Yeah. So we figured, wouldn't it be weird if people had something like this?

00:07:58.220 --> 00:08:00.940
Wouldn't that be like, end up with all these strange implications?

00:08:00.940 --> 00:08:13.820
Because we kind of designed a business model as an art project around, well, if you provide this information, then maybe the thing that you might get, you might get an incentive to basically film everyone else doing this if you got cheaper insurance premiums.

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:28.200
And because like insurance companies don't need to disclose how they price you, you could have this idea where you could present the idea that you're pricing people off the roads for bad driving, but instead create this kind of horrifying dystopian hellscape where everyone's continually filming each other.

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:31.120
And that seemed more interesting than making a film.

00:08:31.120 --> 00:08:33.700
That's a pretty interesting social experiment.

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:34.160
Yeah.

00:08:34.160 --> 00:08:34.820
Where'd it go?

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:35.000
Yeah.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.440
So, well, we, so there's the other thing.

00:08:37.440 --> 00:08:43.020
There is an idea called, if you look at work with IP, like intellectual property, there's a phrase called prior arts.

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:46.120
And we thought, oh my God, this is, this is, this is horrifying what we're building.

00:08:46.120 --> 00:08:48.900
Well, now we've explored this, the implications are terrifying.

00:08:48.900 --> 00:08:55.320
So we figured, well, one thing we can do is let's take this prior art idea quite literally and like put it in a gallery.

00:08:55.320 --> 00:08:57.060
So it's literally prior art.

00:08:57.060 --> 00:09:02.600
And if you do it that way, then you cannot patent it because it's kind of toxic and no one can make any money off it.

00:09:02.600 --> 00:09:04.640
And like, of course we were naive students.

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:05.240
All right.

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:10.120
So like, I'm pretty sure large companies have found ways to make money out of data now.

00:09:10.480 --> 00:09:13.280
But this was an idea like, yeah, as if anyone would really do that.

00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:13.560
Right.

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:17.940
And that was kind of my first exposure into coding.

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:22.480
And that was, that was actually Ruby initially with little bits of C and stuff.

00:09:22.480 --> 00:09:24.760
But I found the two of them quite difficult.

00:09:24.760 --> 00:09:27.300
And especially back then.

00:09:27.300 --> 00:09:32.320
And then when I graduated, I was looking for something similarly interesting and out there.

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:37.560
And I couldn't find much, but the person who I built that with, I mean, he only built this because he was doing a cognitive science course.

00:09:37.560 --> 00:09:41.180
And he thought some of the ideas, some of my ideas were kind of funny.

00:09:41.180 --> 00:09:45.920
We ended up setting up a company where we figured we're only going to work on open source, nice things.

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:54.680
And we ended up working in a co-working space and find ourselves working on bits of Django or doing some kind of Internet of Things related stuff.

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:58.640
And I think I've just shared a link to some of the earliest code I've ever contributed to.

00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:05.500
And like my first Python as a person who could barely write HTML was diving straight into Twisted.

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:10.440
And oh, I'm not sure that was the first code I should have written, right?

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:14.520
Yeah, that's definitely mind bending that async stuff.

00:10:14.520 --> 00:10:21.860
Well, look, if you can start out by building, like recreating dash cams in the software and hardware side,

00:10:21.860 --> 00:10:26.100
and then you can go contribute or work on code that's for Twisted, I think you'll be all right.

00:10:26.100 --> 00:10:28.340
Well, that was actually a kind of interesting project.

00:10:28.340 --> 00:10:30.960
That project, the Twisted stuff, there's a story around that, actually.

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:33.480
So what we were doing, we're in this co-working space.

00:10:34.160 --> 00:10:41.120
And we were thinking, well, wouldn't it be cool if you could help people understand that there is an environmental impact to how we use buildings?

00:10:41.120 --> 00:10:51.600
And maybe if you can do something what we might call now, like flexible pricing around co-working space to kind of incentivize people to use it when it's not so much.

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:56.440
So think of it like, I don't know, load balancing or demand shifting, but with people rather than like servers.

00:10:56.440 --> 00:11:06.000
So we ended up working on some things to basically work out the carbon footprint per person per hour of space by inferring presence on Wi-Fi,

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.600
but looking at it by tracking the MAC addresses in a co-working space.

00:11:08.600 --> 00:11:14.940
Because we could pretty much figure it out that if there is maybe, if every single person has a phone and a laptop,

00:11:15.180 --> 00:11:19.140
if you can count the laptops and the phones and you can more or less associate them with each other,

00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:22.640
then you get a rough idea of occupancy and usage of spaces here.

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:26.200
And if you know how much energy you're using, you can work that out as well.

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:30.460
Right. And mostly that's probably heating, cooling, that kind of stuff, not people plugging in their laptops.

00:11:30.460 --> 00:11:36.840
So if there's one person versus 10 people, it costs almost 10 times as much for that one person in terms of energy.

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:37.520
Absolutely. Right.

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:39.200
So this was one thing you could do.

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:44.060
So if you can encourage people to kind of scrunch together to use that space more efficiently,

00:11:44.060 --> 00:11:47.220
then you've got a much more efficient use of that space per person.

00:11:47.220 --> 00:11:53.320
And if you think in terms of not buildings, but providing working space, again, which is kind of what you see now,

00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:58.260
there are so many kind of lucrative businesses that I've failed to kind of take forward.

00:11:58.260 --> 00:12:00.940
You were really early at a lot of these things, right?

00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:03.360
Yeah, we ended up doing a lot of stuff like that.

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:07.240
And that was my exposure to messing around with like Python and Twisted because we said,

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:10.740
oh, yeah, we could do that because we figured you're just reading RFID cards, right?

00:12:10.740 --> 00:12:17.940
And then my friend Fred Fix, who now lives in Berlin and as a CTO of some of the same companies we were working on part time with that,

00:12:17.940 --> 00:12:24.520
we basically had to find a way to make these things speak to some parts of a building to trigger some actuators for sliding doors to work.

00:12:24.520 --> 00:12:29.800
And in order to do that, we figured, well, we use Twisted and we need a server to make a door work.

00:12:29.800 --> 00:12:33.560
So the link I've shared is door D because it's like a demon for a door.

00:12:33.560 --> 00:12:34.240
Oh, nice.

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:35.300
Yeah.

